Preface

The following bar charts the counts of penguins samples broken down by species, year, sex, and year of collection.

# use the same fill colors as on the palmer penguins website
penguin_colors <- c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")

by_species <-
  ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_bar(aes(x = species, fill = species)) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = penguin_colors) + 
  labs(x = "Species", y = "Count") +
  guides(fill = "none")  # turn off fill legend because it's redundant with x-axis

by_island <-
  ggplot(penguins, aes(x = island)) + 
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "Island", y = "Count")

by_sex <- 
  ggplot(penguins, aes(x = sex, fill = sex)) +   
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = "Sex", y = "Count") +
  guides(fill = "none") 

by_year <- 
  ggplot(penguins, aes(x = year)) +   
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Count")

# lay out the subplots using the patchwork package
((by_species | by_island) /
 (by_sex     | by_year))

Problem 03

Faceting in ggplot is akin to group_by() in dplyr. It allows us to generate visualizations by grouping on variables of interest. The example below illustrate how to use facet_grid to group on the sex variable in the data set.

penguins |>
  filter(!is.na(sex)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = island, fill=species)) + 
    geom_bar() + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = penguin_colors) + 
    facet_grid(row=vars(sex)) + 
    labs(x = "Island", y = "Count")

Part a

Modify the code above to generate the following figure that facets on both the sex and year variables.

Part b

What did we learn about the the four variables of species, sex, island, and year that we didnât know from the individual plots?

Problem 05

Plots like histograms, box plots, and density plots are âsummaryâ visualizations based on summarizing aspects of the underlying data. When the data are of moderate size, it is often useful to display the raw data in combination with the summary visualization. In the code below we show how to do this by layering geoms.

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = body_mass_g)) +
  # histogram is first layer
  geom_histogram(bins=25, alpha=0.65) +
  # jitter points are second layer
  geom_jitter(aes(y = 0),
              height = 1,
              size=0.85,
              alpha=0.5) +
  labs(x = "Body mass (g)", y = "Count") +
  guides(fill = "none")

Part a

Modify the code above to produce a plot like the following:

Part b

A violin plot (geom_violin) allows a similar comparison to the above faceted histogram, without the need to facet.

Modify the code below using to produce the plot that follows.

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_violin(alpha=0.35) +
  labs(x = "Species", y = "Body mass (g)") +
  guides(fill = "none", color = "none")

Problem 06

The following biplot shows the relationship between bill length and depth.

penguins |>
  filter(!is.na(sex)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = bill_length_mm, 
             y = bill_depth_mm,
             shape = species,
             color = species)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.75) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = penguin_colors) +
  labs(x = "Bill length (mm)",
       y = "Bill depth (mm)")
